   2010},
Organization = {Amer Chem Soc, Phys Chem Div; Silicon Graph Inc},
Abstract = {When using Hartree-Fock (HF) trial wave functions in quantum Monte Carlo
   calculations, one faces, in case of HF instabilities, the HF symmetry
   dilemma in choosing between the symmetry-adapted solution of higher HF
   energy and symmetry-broken solutions of lower HF energies. In this work,
   we have examined the HF symmetry dilemma in hydrogen rings which present
   singlet instabilities for sufficiently large rings. We have found that
   the symmetry-adapted HF wave function gives a lower energy both in
   variational Monte Carlo and in fixed-node diffusion Monte Carlo. This
   indicates that the symmetry-adapted wave function has more accurate
   nodes than the symmetry-broken wave functions, and thus suggests that
   spatial symmetry is an important criterion for selecting good trial wave
   functions. (C) 2012 American Chemical Society},
