Year = {1996},
Volume = {54},
Number = {6},
Pages = {4810-4814},
Month = {Dec},
Abstract = {Most approximate exchange-correlation functionals used within
   density-functional theory are constructed as the sum of two distinct
   contributions for exchange and correlation. Separating the exchange
   component from the entire functional is useful since, for exchange,
   exact relations exist under uniform density scaling and spin scaling. In
   the past, accurate exchange-correlation potentials have been generated
   from essentially exact densities but they have not been correctly
   decomposed into their separate exchange and correlation components
   (except for two-electron systems). Using a recently proposed method,
   equivalent to the solution of an optimized effective potential problem
   with the corresponding orbitals replaced by the exact Kohn-Sham
   orbitals, we obtain the separation according to the density functional
   theory definition. We compare the results for the Ne and Be atoms with
   those obtained by the previously used approximate separation scheme.},
